A-Eng. HB 4082
1 (B) Allow the city to amend its conceptual plan and resubmit it as a petition to Metro
2 under this section.
3 (c) If Metro determines that a petition does comply, notwithstanding any other provision
4 of ORS chapter 197A, Metro shall adopt amendments to its urban growth boundary to include
5 the site in the petition, unless the amendment would result in more than 300 total net resi-
6 dential acres added under this subsection.
7 (d) Metro may not conduct a hearing to review or select petitions or adopt amendments
8 to its urban growth boundary under this section.
9 (e) Sites added to the Metro urban growth boundary under this section do not affect the
10 maximum acreage of sites that may be added under section 51 (3) or (4), chapter 110, Oregon
11 Laws 2024.
12 (5) A city that adds or petitions to add a site under this section:
13 (a) Is not required to demonstrate need for housing lands or affordable housing under
14 section 52, chapter 110, Oregon Laws 2024.
15 (b) May additionally add a site to its urban growth boundary under section 50 (1) or 56,
16 chapter 110, Oregon Laws 2024, or section 2, chapter 341, Oregon Laws 2025, or may petition
17 to add a site under section 51, chapter 110, Oregon Laws 2024.
18 (c) Must first adopt a conceptual plan as described in section 55, chapter 110, Oregon
19 Laws 2024, except that the conceptual plan:
20 (A) Is not required to establish the density or housing types under section 55 (3)(a),
21 chapter 110, Oregon Laws 2024, for lands that will be sited for manufactured dwellings, pre-
22 fabricated structures or manufactured dwelling parks.
23 (B) May be zoned for residential densities of eight units per net residential acre in a city
24 with a population of 30,000 or greater, notwithstanding section 55 (3)(a)(C)(i) or (ii), chapter
25 110, Oregon Laws 2024.
26 (C) Is not required to comply with section 55 (3)(f), chapter 110, Oregon Laws 2024.
27 (D) Must include requirements that ensure that at least 80 percent of dwelling units, not
28 including manufactured dwellings or prefabricated structures, are subject to affordability
29 restrictions, including but not limited to affordable housing covenants, as described in ORS
30 456.270 to 456.295, that require for a period of not less than 30 years that the units be avail-
31 able and affordable, with or without government assistance, for rent or purchase by house-
32 holds with an income of 120 percent of the area median income or less.
33 (E) Must require that all land within the housing development, other than land in a
34 manufactured dwelling park or used for manufactured dwellings or prefabricated structures,
35 is designated as housing for older persons. This requirement may take the form of zoning
36 designations or overlays, master planning, conditions of approval, restrictive covenants or
37 declarations as defined in ORS 94.550 or 100.005, that:
38 (i) Require the owner of the land to develop a plan to use the land only as housing for
39 older persons. The plan must include policies and procedures as described in 24 C.F.R.
40 100.306;
41 (ii) Are enforceable by the city;
42 (iii) Contain financial penalties for noncompliance; and
43 (iv) Require that at least 80 percent of the residential units comply with the “Type B”
44 requirements applicable to units as set forth in the Standard for Accessible and Usable
45 Buildings and Facilities published by the International Code Council and as referenced by the
